cs.CY, cs.SI, cs.SOC, cs.HC, cs.IR 

This paper likely belongs to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CY (Computers and Society) as it investigates social disparities and biases in online platforms. It also likely belongs to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as it analyzes users' position in the social network. Additionally, it could belong to cs.SOC (Social and Economic Networks) as it explores gender differences in success and failure. It may also belong to cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) as it discusses the impact of design choices on the site. Finally, it could belong to cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as it analyzes recommendation systems on the site.
